\begin{IDEA}
**Title: Asymmetric Predictive Information Flow from TSLA-Idiosyncratic Volatility to Systematic Factor Variance**

This research investigates whether the time-varying idiosyncratic volatility of TSLA, isolated via a GARCH(1,1) filter, serves as a lead indicator for the broader panel’s systematic volatility. By stripping the market and sector factor contributions from TSLA's returns, we extract the pure idiosyncratic shock series and model its conditional variance. We then employ a Granger-causality framework to test if innovations in this idiosyncratic GARCH process precede shifts in the realized volatility of the market factor. This approach specifically targets the unique dynamic signal embedded in the TSLA series to determine if high-beta idiosyncratic instability acts as a precursor to systemic risk regime changes within the two-factor structure. The study concludes by quantifying the extent to which TSLA’s specific volatility clustering provides incremental predictive power for the covariance matrix of the remaining nine assets, beyond what is explained by the constant factor loadings.
\end{IDEA}


